# Always Commit + Always Push

After finishing a meaningful change set (code, figures, docs, PPT, scripts):

1. **Always commit** — every change must leave a git record (message focuses on why).
2. **Always push** — push to the tracked remote immediately after a successful commit.
3. Do **not** wait for the user to say “push”. Only skip push if there is no remote / push fails (then report the error).
4. Do **not** use destructive git operations (`push --force`, hard reset) unless the user explicitly asks.
5. Follow normal commit hygiene: stage only relevant files; never commit secrets (`.env`, credentials).

This overrides any default “do not push unless asked” guidance for this user’s workflows.
